Event-driven architecture allows services to communicate by producing and consuming events instead of making direct requests.

Benefits include:

* Loose coupling
* Improved scalability
* Faster response to business events

For example, when a customer places an order, an event can trigger inventory updates, payment processing, shipment creation, and email notifications simultaneously.

A real-life use case is logistics companies automatically updating shipment status across multiple systems.

Another example is IoT environments where sensor events trigger automated workflows.

Event-driven architecture enables responsive and scalable applications.
